I think the real problem is the definition of "equality". People don't realise that talking about equality without defining it is next to useless. It's a term that is way too broad.

Cassie Jaye is a documentary film maker who set out to make a film about Men's Right's Activists (MRAs) from a feminist perspective. So she went and interview the most prominent MRAs such as Warren Farrell, Karen Straughan and Paul Elam. Her plan was to expose them as a group of misogynists trying to reverse women's rights. But as the filming and editing progressed, she became increasingly understanding of their point of view. No doubt some MRA leaders have tactics and rhetoric that are, IMO, a little questionable but more often than not, they have a point when it comes to inequalities facing men. In the end, she decided she was no longer a feminist and the film became The Red Pill:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wLzeakKC6fE

Now Cassie Jaye had one of the most insightful comment regarding feminism and equality I've ever heard when she was interviewed on Michele Carroll's show. She looked at the definition of feminism on wikipedia and it reads:

_"Feminism is a range of social movements, political movements, and ideologies that aim to define, establish, and achieve the political, economic, personal, and social equality of the sexes."_

She remarked that the key word there was "define". Define political, economic, personal, and social equality. And that's the problem with feminism, it has a very woman-centric and ideological definition of equality. Feminism decides what equality means and it's never fair for a player to also be making the rules.

Here is the segment in question:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uVXK4rWHtIs

And the full interview:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KQ44TjFiuqY

And this is the unedited interview Cassie Jaye had with Fred Hayward, a father's right campaigner. These two clips are interesting because 1- he appears to be nice guy, 2- it talks about that definition of equality and the double standards you see in the feminist definition and 3- he talks about three of the most demonstrable forms of discrimination affecting men, ie father's rights, zero reproductive rights for men and the military draft.

Part 1: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rjpdz1WY2zg

Part 2: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rjpdz1WY2zg

So we really need to have a discussion about what equality means rather than using it as broadly as we do. But in order to do that, we need to include men in the conversation on gender equality but feminism refuses to do that.
